619	\section{2-affine cover Mayer-Vietoris square (iter-028)}
620	\label{sec:scheme_affineCoverMVSquare}
621	
622	After iter-027's file split the abstract Mayer-Vietoris LES on $\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$ is complete and self-contained in this chapter. The next step toward Serre finiteness on a proper $k$-curve is to provide a \emph{specialisation} of the abstract LES to the geometric setting in which Serre finiteness is actually proved: a quasi-compact separated $k$-scheme $X$ admitting an open cover by two affines $U_1, U_2$ whose intersection $U_1 \cap U_2$ is again affine.
623	
624	\subsection{Why this is the natural iter-028 target}
625	
626	Serre's finiteness theorem on a proper $k$-curve is proved by Čech-cohomology computation on a 2-affine cover: the sheaf cohomology $H^i(X, \mathcal F)$ vanishes for $i \geq 2$ (because the cover has only two pieces and the Čech complex is concentrated in degrees $0, 1$), and is finite-dimensional over $k$ in degrees $0$ and $1$ because each $\mathcal F(U_j)$ is a finitely generated module over the affine ring of $U_j$ and the cohomology is a sub/quotient of finite-dimensional pieces. The Mayer-Vietoris LES we built in iter-014 $\to$ iter-026 is the categorical engine that lets us extract these vanishing/finiteness facts \emph{abstractly} from the affine vanishing $H^{>0}(\Spec A, \mathcal F) = 0$ — but to use it on $X$ rather than on $U_1 \sqcup U_2$, we need a Mayer-Vietoris square whose total piece $X_4$ is $X$ itself, not just $U_1 \sqcup U_2$. The total-cover hypothesis $U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$ is therefore load-bearing.
627	
628	Mathlib provides $\Opens.\mayerVietorisSquare \,\colon\, \Opens\,T \to \Opens\,T \to (\Opens.\grothendieckTopology\,T).\MayerVietorisSquare$ (\texttt{Mathlib/Topology/Sheaves/MayerVietoris.lean}), which produces an abstract square with $X_1 = U_1 \sqcap U_2$, $X_2 = U_1$, $X_3 = U_2$, $X_4 = U_1 \sqcup U_2$, but does \emph{not} record the affineness of any of these pieces and does \emph{not} express that $U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$ when that is the case. The iter-028 scaffold target therefore packages the four affineness conditions ($\IsAffineOpen\,U_1$, $\IsAffineOpen\,U_2$, $\IsAffineOpen\,(U_1 \sqcap U_2)$) plus the cover hypothesis ($U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$) into a bundled structure $\AffineCoverMVSquare\,X$ on a single scheme $X$, and exposes the underlying Mathlib MV square as an accessor. Downstream Serre-finiteness work can then unpack the structure into (a) Čech-/MV-LES inputs and (b) affine-vanishing inputs.
629	
630	\subsection{Mathlib gap and design}
631	
632	There is no $\AffineCoverMVSquare$ analog in Mathlib; the abstract $\MayerVietorisSquare$ exists for any preordered category with a Grothendieck topology, but the affineness conditions (which are scheme-specific) are not in scope at that level. The iter-028 scaffold introduces the bundled scheme-flavored structure, with the four corner accessors definitionally equal to $U_1 \sqcap U_2$, $U_1$, $U_2$, $U_1 \sqcup U_2$ via the Mathlib $\Opens.\mayerVietorisSquare$ constructor (probe-confirmed $\rfl$, see Lemma~\ref{lem:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_corners}). The cover hypothesis $\cover \,\colon\, U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$ is recorded but not consumed by $\toMayerVietorisSquare$; iter-029+ Serre-finiteness lemmas will use it to identify $X_4$ with $\top$ and hence read off cohomology of the whole scheme $X$.
633	
634	\begin{definition}[2-affine MV square on a scheme, iter-028]
635	  \label{def:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare}
636	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.AffineCoverMVSquare}
637	  \leanok
638	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime}
639	  Let $X : \Scheme.\{u\}$. The structure $X.\AffineCoverMVSquare$ has fields
640	  \begin{itemize}
641	    \item $U_1, U_2 : X.\Opens$ (two open subschemes of $X$);
642	    \item $\mathtt{isAffineOpen\_U_1} \,\colon\, \IsAffineOpen\,U_1$;
643	    \item $\mathtt{isAffineOpen\_U_2} \,\colon\, \IsAffineOpen\,U_2$;
644	    \item $\mathtt{isAffineOpen\_inf} \,\colon\, \IsAffineOpen\,(U_1 \sqcap U_2)$;
645	    \item $\cover \,\colon\, U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$.
646	  \end{itemize}
647	  Equivalently: a $2$-affine open cover of $X$ together with the hypothesis that the pairwise intersection is affine.
648	\end{definition}
649	
650	\begin{definition}[Underlying Mayer-Vietoris square accessor, iter-028]
651	  \label{def:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_toMayerVietorisSquare}
652	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.AffineCoverMVSquare.toMayerVietorisSquare}
653	  \leanok
654	  \uses{def:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare}
655	  Let $X : \Scheme.\{u\}$ and $S : X.\AffineCoverMVSquare$. The underlying abstract MV square is
656	  \[
657	    S.\toMayerVietorisSquare \;:=\; \Opens.\mayerVietorisSquare\,S.U_1\,S.U_2 \;\colon\; (\Opens.\grothendieckTopology\,X.\toTopCat).\MayerVietorisSquare.
658	  \]
659	  This is the bridge from the geometric input (the bundled affine cover $S$) to the categorical input (a $\MayerVietorisSquare$) the abstract MV-LES theorem $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequence\_exact}$ consumes.
660	\end{definition}
661	
662	\begin{lemma}[Corner identifications, iter-028]
663	  \label{lem:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_corners}
664	  \uses{def:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_toMayerVietorisSquare}
665	  In the setting of Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_toMayerVietorisSquare} the four corners of $S.\toMayerVietorisSquare$ collapse to
666	  \[
667	    X_1 = U_1 \sqcap U_2, \quad X_2 = U_1, \quad X_3 = U_2, \quad X_4 = U_1 \sqcup U_2,
668	  \]
669	  where each equality holds by $\rfl$. (The plan-agent probe in iter-028 confirms the four \lstinline{rfl}-equalities; they are not formalised as named lemmas but are recorded here for downstream consumers' definitional unfolding.)
670	\end{lemma}
671	
672	\subsection{Use in Serre finiteness}
673	
674	For a proper geometrically integral $k$-curve $C$ a $2$-affine cover with affine intersection always exists (e.g.\ remove a closed point to get one affine, remove another to get the second; their intersection is the curve minus two points, again affine on a $k$-curve). The bundle $C.\AffineCoverMVSquare$ then feeds the iter-029+ Serre-finiteness chain:
675	\begin{enumerate}
676	  \item The MV-LES applied to $S.\toMayerVietorisSquare$ and $\toModuleKSheaf\,C$ gives a $5$-term sequence relating $H^0$ and $H^1$ of $X = \top$, $U_1$, $U_2$, $U_1 \cap U_2$.
677	  \item The cover hypothesis $S.\cover \,\colon\, U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$ identifies the $X_4$ piece with $\top$ (i.e.\ all of $C$).
678	  \item The affineness of $U_1$, $U_2$, $U_1 \cap U_2$ collapses $H^{>0}$ on those pieces (Serre vanishing on affines), reducing the LES to a $3$-term sequence relating $H^0(C, \mathcal O_C)$, $H^0(U_j, \mathcal O)$ and $H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$.
679	  \item Each $H^0$ piece is a $k$-module given by a finite ring computation, hence finite-dimensional, hence so is $H^1$.
680	\end{enumerate}
681	Step 4 is the actual Serre finiteness; iter-028 lands only the bundle structure $\AffineCoverMVSquare$ and the abstract-MV-square accessor $\toMayerVietorisSquare$. Iter-029 (next) lands the four corner-identification $\mathtt{simp}$ lemmas that drive Step 2 plus the abstract-LES specialisation that drives Step 1. The remaining steps (Step 3 + Step 4) are iter-030+ work.
682	
683	\section{Companion simp lemmas + abstract LES specialisation (iter-029)}
684	\label{sec:scheme_affineCoverMVSquare_iter029}
685	
686	Iter-029 appends six companion declarations to Section~\ref{sec:scheme_affineCoverMVSquare} (or rather, to the same Lean section \lstinline{section AffineCoverMVSquare}, immediately after $\toMayerVietorisSquare$). They are the natural follow-on to iter-028: the four corner-identification $\mathtt{simp}$ lemmas materialising Lemma~\ref{lem:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_corners} as named, $\mathtt{simp}$-tagged lemmas, plus a sheaf-parameterised specialisation of the abstract MV-LES sequence and exactness theorem (iter-022/iter-026) to the bundled $\AffineCoverMVSquare$ data. The plan-agent has probe-verified all six declarations together against the post-iter-028 file with $\{\text{success: true, diagnostics: []}\}$.
687	
688	\subsection{Why this is the natural iter-029 target}
689	
690	The iter-028 close gives us the bundled $\AffineCoverMVSquare$ structure with the abstract-MV-square accessor; iter-030+ Serre-finiteness work will need (a) named $\mathtt{simp}$ lemmas for the four corners (so that downstream $\mathtt{simp}$ calls can rewrite $S.\toMayerVietorisSquare.\toSquare.X_j$ to the underlying $U_1$, $U_2$, $U_1 \sqcap U_2$, $\top$), and (b) an LES specialisation that takes a generic $\AffineCoverMVSquare\,X$ and a generic sheaf $F$, returning the $5$-term Mayer-Vietoris sequence and its exactness witness. Both are routine specialisations of the iter-022/iter-026 abstract API; the one piece of substantive content is the $X_4 = \top$ identification, which uses the $\cover$ field of $\AffineCoverMVSquare$ and is therefore the only non-$\rfl$ corner identification.
691	
692	The LES specialisation is parameterised over a generic sheaf $F$ rather than specialising to $\toModuleKSheaf\,C$ directly, so that downstream consumers can reuse it across different sheaf flavours (the structure sheaf, the relative differentials sheaf, etc.). The $\toModuleKSheaf$-specific application is iter-030+ work.
